  "summary": "During a birthday celebration for Miss Bonnie Bunn, guests gather at Miss Blacklock's home. Dora Bunner discusses her age and a gift of eggs from Miss Quincannon, while Miss Blacklock notes that Julia provided a box of chocolates. Miss Bunn also displays a new diamond leaf brooch. During the birthday dinner, Patrick jokingly refers to the cake as \"delicious death,\" prompting Miss Blacklock to hush him so as not to offend Midge. After the meal, Julia expresses feeling unwell, attributing it to the cake.\n\nThe conversation shifts when Miss Chickchaff mentions seeing a man who looks like a soldier peering around the chicken coop. Julia identifies him as a detective sent to protect Miss Blacklock. This leads to a discussion regarding the police investigation; Edmund Swetnam suggests that everyone is under suspicion and that the police are using a pretext to catch a murderer on the spot. This remark causes an awkward silence before the group moves to listen to the news, which covers the threat of nuclear war.\n\nAfter the guests depart, Miss Bunn retires to bed, complaining of a headache and an inability to find her aspirin. Julia and Patrick toast Midge, with Patrick again calling the food \"delicious death.\" Later, Miss Blacklock pulls Philippa aside to discuss her recent worries. Miss Blacklock reveals that she visited her lawyer, Mr. Beddingfield, to prepare a new will in case of unforeseen circumstances. She informs a shocked Philippa that, in addition to an inheritance for Bonnie, everything else will be left to her because \"there's no one else.\"",
